      <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-gray-900">Work-From-Home Burnout: How to Set Boundaries and Protect Your Mental Health</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-8 text-gray-600">When your office is also your home, work never really stops. Here is how to set boundaries, recognize early warning signs, and prevent WFH burnout before it takes over.</p>

      <div class="mt-10 prose prose-lg prose-gray max-w-none">
        <div class="rounded-2xl bg-red-50 border border-red-200 p-6 not-prose">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-red-800">WFH Burnout Is Real</p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-red-700">A 2026 survey found that 48% of remote workers report feeling burned out — higher than the 38% of in-office workers. The causes are unique: blurred work-life boundaries, social isolation, "always on" culture, and the pressure to prove you are working. Recognizing the signs early is critical.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Recognize the Warning Signs</h2>
        <p>Burnout does not happen overnight. It builds gradually. Common early warning signs include: dreading the start of your workday, irritability with colleagues or family, difficulty concentrating on tasks you used to handle easily, physical exhaustion that rest does not fix, and checking work messages at all hours — including weekends and late at night.</p>
        <p>If you are nodding at multiple items on this list, it is time to make changes.</p>

        <h2>1. Create a Physical Shutdown Ritual</h2>
        <p>When you work in an office, the commute home gives you a clear transition between "work brain" and "home brain." At home, that transition does not exist. Create one intentionally: close your laptop (fully shut it down, not just sleep mode), put away your work devices in a drawer or cabinet, change into comfortable clothes, and do something physical — a walk, a workout, cooking. This signals to your nervous system that the workday is over.</p>

        <h2>2. Set Hard Boundaries With Your Calendar</h2>
        <p>Block off time on your calendar for: start of day (first 30 minutes), lunch (a real break), and end of day (last 30 minutes). Mark these as "busy" or "private." This prevents meetings from creeping into your personal buffer zones. The 30-minute buffer at the end of the day is especially important — it gives you time to wrap up, not frantically rush from a 5pm meeting to "home mode."</p>

        <h2>3. Have a "Work-Free Zone"</h2>
        <p>Designate at least one area of your home where you never work — ideally your bedroom. Your brain needs places that are purely for rest and relaxation. If you check work email in bed, your brain learns that bed is a place for work stress. Over time, this wrecks your sleep quality.</p>

        <h2>4. Communicate Your Boundaries Clearly</h2>
        <p>Tell your manager and team explicitly: "I am offline after 6pm and on weekends. If something is truly urgent, call me." Most "urgent" Slack messages can wait until morning. By stating your boundaries clearly, you give yourself permission to actually follow them — and you set an example for your teammates.</p>

        <h2>5. Schedule Non-Work Social Time</h2>
        <p>Remote work removes casual social interaction — the coffee machine chat, the lunch walk, the desk drop-by. These interactions are not a waste of time; they are essential for mental health. Schedule at least one social activity per week that is not work-related: a friend coffee, a group hobby, a sports team, a volunteer shift. In-person, not video call.</p>

        <h2>6. Take Your Vacation Days</h2>
        <p>Remote workers take fewer vacation days than office workers. The logic is: "I am already at home, why do I need a break?" This is a trap. Time off is not just about escaping the office — it is about mental recovery and perspective. If you have unused vacation days sitting there, use them. Even a 3-day weekend makes a measurable difference.</p>

        <h2>7. Exercise Is Not Optional</h2>
        <p>When you work from home, you lose "incidental movement": walking to the bus, taking the stairs, going to lunch. This adds up to 300-500 fewer calories burned per day, but the mental health impact is even bigger. Regular exercise is one of the most effective treatments for mild to moderate depression and anxiety. Schedule it like a meeting and treat it as non-negotiable.</p>

        <p>If you are feeling the effects of WFH burnout, you are not alone. Small, consistent changes make a big difference over time. Start with one boundary — the shutdown ritual — and build from there. Want to assess your overall remote work wellness? Try our <a href="/tools/productivity-scorecard/">WFH Productivity Scorecard</a>.</p>
